Analysis of Bike Sharing Rides with Bay Wheels Data¶

by Anastasia Kaliakova¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Bay Wheels is a bike sharing service available throughout Bay Area of west coast USA. It is a affordible and accessible way of transportation. The company went through several name changes and acquisitions. It started as in August 2013 as Bay Area Bike Share. Later it was re-launched as Ford GoBike in a partnership with Ford Motor Company. 2017. In June 2019 renamed to Bay Wheels after acquisition by Lyft. Bay Wheels system currently has over 2,600 bicycles in 262 stations across San Francisco, East Bay and San Jose. Rides are available to people through Bay Wheels subscription and Lyft app.

My motivation for this project is to expand the exploratory and explanatory data visualization skills by analyzing bike sharing trends by location in Bay Area: San Francisco, Oakland, San Jose. My goal is to practice exploratory data visualization during the process of data wrangling to uncover interesting features of the dataset and to find problems that must be cleaned. My second goal is to apply explanatory data visualization techniques to comunicate my findings about different bike sahring trends for San Francisco, Oakland and San Jose.

Bay Wheels makes its data avalable here: https://www.lyft.com/bikes/bay-wheels/system-data

Collecting and loadig the data¶

In order to use the data for this analisys I first had to collect data from the link provided above. The Bay Wheels trip history data was presented in multiple zip folders for each month of the year starting from 2017 through July 2019. I first downloaded each folder and then used glob() function to read each file from the foulder path into a list to later combine it into one dataset.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

After collecting and combining all of the bike trip data avalable I have a dataset containing over 3 million entries (rows) and 17 colunmns. Original columns of dataset include following:

  • Trip Duration (seconds)
  • Start Time and Date
  • End Time and Date
  • Start Station ID
  • Start Station Name
  • Start Station Latitude
  • Start Station Longitude
  • End Station ID
  • End Station Name
  • End Station Latitude
  • End Station Longitude
  • Bike ID
  • User Type (Subscriber or Customer Subscriber = Member or Customer = Casual)
  • Member Year of Birth
  • Member Gender

The first observation of columns shows that most variables are categorical in nature ("Member Gender", "User Type"). There is a small number of numeric variables ("Trip Duration"). The dataset also includes interesting variable types releted to time and geographical location which could be usefull for creating new variables but also would requre cleaning.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The Bay Wheels stations are available three main areas of the Bay Area: San Francisco, the East Bay, and San Jose. I would like to explore how trends of bike-sharing vary for each of those areas.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The dataset is not separated by city, therefore the feauture that will help me solve this limitation are the collection of columns containing longitude and latitude of bike stations.

In order to explore number of bike rides acording to time variables available in the set I grouped the data by year and by year and month. The year of 2018 shows the most amount of bike rides and the 2017 is the least. However being aware that the dataset does not contain equal number of month for each year it is not the best way to guage the trend.

In my opinion ploting the line of distribution of bike rides along the whole available time frame allows for more accurate representation of data. I used groupby() by month and year and agg() function to aggregate based on bike id count as presented below.

def make_city(start_lat, end_lat, start_long, end_long):
    if (min_lat_sf <= start_lat <= max_lat_sf and min_lat_sf <= end_lat <= max_lat_sf) and (min_long_sf <= start_long <= max_long_sf and min_long_sf <= end_long <= max_long_sf):
        return 'San Francisco'
    elif (min_lat_sj <= start_lat <= max_lat_sj and min_lat_sj <= end_lat <= max_lat_sj) and (min_long_sj <= start_long <= max_long_sj and min_long_sj <= end_long <= max_long_sj):
        return 'San Jose'
    elif (min_lat_ok <= start_lat <= max_lat_ok and min_lat_ok <= end_lat <= max_lat_ok) and (min_long_ok <= start_long <= max_long_ok and min_long_ok <= end_long <= max_long_ok):
        return 'Oakland'
    else:
        return 'other'
    

df_clean['city'] = np.vectorize(make_city)(df_clean['start_station_latitude'], df_clean['end_station_latitude'], df_clean['start_station_longitude'], df_clean['end_station_longitude'])

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Most the variables in the dataset are categorical: "Member Gender", "User Type", "Rental_access_method". The male gender of riders (2560529 members) significantly dominating the over Female gender (843180 members). For the User Type the most popular is Sudscriber type (3073025 members). The numeric variables include: "Trip Duration", "Age" both were found to have large number of outliers. For both of the variables I used box plot to explore outliers and to find maximum values, maximum age was around 60 years old and maximum trip duaration around 30 min. The histogram of trip duration showed data to be extreamly skwed to the right, therefore I applied a logarithmic transformation its x-axis for beter representation of data. The overall number of bike rides was found to be highest around March of 2019 preceded by sharp decline in use in the end of 2018. San Francisco showed to be the most popular city for shared bike rides.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Two of the variables I investigated in this set were not provided for me in the original dataset. The "Age" variable was not provided, I had to create it using the "Member Year of Birth" variable. It serves as a second major numeric variable in this analisys. I also used variable types releted geographical location: "Start Station Latitude", "Start Station Longitude", "End Station Latitude", "End Station Longitude" to create additional categorical variable "City" to explore data by each city. In addition to that I created new variable for trip duration in minutes. I converted variables for start and end of trips to date/time type. That allowed me to group data by year and month.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

I observed weak correlation between two numeric variables of the dataset, age and trip duration. However, scatter plot of the relations showed that older people are taking less longer trips and that most of the trips are attempted by people in the age between 25 and 40 years old. Female bikers tend to take slightly longer trips. Population of bikers in San Francisco tend to be the oldest, and yongest population of riders in San Jose. I have noticed that comparing gender and user type distribution only besed on count of trips is confusing due to very big difference on total number of users between three cities. Therefore, I decided to use percentages. I have found that San Jose contains the largest percent of male bikers and Oakland has the lergest percent of female bikers. Among three cities the most percentage of bikers the largest percent of subscriber user type is in San Jose, and largest percent of customer user type is in San Francisco.
